04132nam a22005175i 9780773562592DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735625927 a10.1515/97807735625922doi  a(DE-B1597)657418  a(OCoLC)1394872286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aUH629.5.C2bC673 1990eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a940.54/75711 aCopp, Terry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBattle Exhaustion :bSoldiers and Psychiatrists in the Canadian Army, 1939-1945 /cBill McAndrew, Terry Copp. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tNo. I Nuts -- tSquare Pegs and Round Holes -- tInto Battle -- tThe D-Day Dodgers -- tIf This War Isn't Over… -- tNormandy -- tProximity, Immediacy, and Expectancy -- tConclusion -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tBibliogratphy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the outset of the Second World War Canadians wanted to avoid the horrors encountered on the western front in 1914-18, one of the most significant of which was "shell shock." Most medical personnel preferred not to assign to combat those who showed neurotic symptoms during training, but this approach was challenged by the Canadian Psychological Association and by the new Personnel Selection Directorate established in 1941. Personnel Selection claimed to be able to distinguish, before training, between those suited and those unsuited to combat duty. However, when Canadian troops went into battle in Italy, the preparatory work seemed to have had little impact. Canadian losses due to "battle exhaustion" were no less than those of other allied forces. Front-line treatment allowed about half of these to return to their units, but eventually a very large number of soldiers were assigned to non-combat roles because it was judged they could no longer function effectively in battle. Similar problems were encountered in Normandy, Belgium, Holland, and Germany. Copp and McAndrew are critical of military commanders who thought strict discipline coupled with high morale from good training and success in battle would keep battle exhaustion in check, and of officers in the Royal Canadian Army Medical Corps who tried to impose theoretical solutions that did not fit the circumstances. The authors show how some doctors, using energy and common sense, contributed to the evolution of contemporary psychiatric ideas about the realities of large-scale psychological casualties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aMcAndrew, Bill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356259240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562592/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles